Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/parliamentary-paper/
Object: A model describing parliamentary papers, their types and their presence in bundles and in series.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/parliamentary-paper/asSeriesitem
Object: Relates a parliamentary paper to the existence of that paper in a series. A paper series item refers to one parliamentary paper. A parliamentary paper may exist as an item in one or more series, or none.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/parliamentary-paper/hasPrivilege
Object: Used to record if parliamentary papers being items in a series indicates that those papers have parliamentary privilege.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/parliamentary-paper/Session
Object: A period during which Parliament is able to conduct business on days of its choosing. A session is within a Parliament period. The first session of a Parliament begins on the same day as the Parliament period and ends on a day named in a subsequent prorogation proclamation. Subsequent sessions within the Parliament period begin and end on dates named in subsequent prorogation proclamations. The final session of a Parliament ends either with prorogation followed by dissolution or with dissolution. Session periods are the same for both Houses.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/parliamentary-paper/belongsTo
Object: Relates a paper series to the session that series belongs to. A paper series may belong to one session, or none, for example: the series of House of Commons papers belonging to the session in which papers in that series are made available.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/parliamentary-paper/ParliamentaryPaperWork
Object: A parliamentary paper as a single intellectual work, as defined in the Functional Requirements for Bibliographic Records specification.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/parliamentary-paper/hasType
Object: Relates a parliamentary paper to the type of that paper. A parliamentary paper may have one or more types.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/parliamentary-paper/inSeries
Object: Relates the existence of a parliamentary paper as an item in a series to the series that the item forms part of. A paper series item forms part of one paper series.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/parliamentary-paper/PaperSeries
Object: A series of parliamentary papers, for example: the Treaty Series.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/parliamentary-paper/prefix
Object: Relates a paper series to the prefix which is combined with a paper series item identifier to form the 'number' of a parliamentary paper as an item in that series.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/parliamentary-paper/ParliamentaryPaper
Object: A parliamentary paper made available to a House.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/parliamentary-paper/PaperType
Object: The type of a paper, for example: bill, statutory instrument, petition, written statement or statement of annual accounts.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/parliamentary-paper/paperTypeParent
Object: Relates one paper type to another in a parent-child relationship. A paper type may have one or more parent paper types, or none. A paper type may have one or more child paper types, or none.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/parliamentary-paper/PaperBundle
Object: A group of related parliamentary papers, called a bundle, for example: a bundle containing a statutory instrument paper and a related explanatory memorandum.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/parliamentary-paper/paperSeriesParent
Object: Relates a paper series to its parent paper series. A paper series may have one parent paper series, or none. A paper series may have one or more child paper series, or none, for example: the Treaty Series of in force treaties is a child series of the Command Papers series.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/parliamentary-paper/expressionOf
Object: Relates a parliamentary paper to the work that paper is an expression of. A parliamentary paper is an expression of one parliamentary paper work. A parliamentary paper work is expressed as one or more parliamentary papers.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/parliamentary-paper/formsPartOf
Object: Relates a parliamentary paper to the paper bundle it forms part of. A parliamentary paper may belong to one or more paper bundles, or none. For example: a single explanatory memorandum may form part of more than one bundle.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/parliamentary-paper/PaperSeriesItem
Object: A parliamentary paper, as it exists as part of a paper series. A parliamentary paper forming part of a series has a number within that series.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/parliamentary-paper/paperSeriesFollows
Object: Relates a paper series to its preceding series. A paper series may follow one series, or none. A paper series may be followed by one series, or none, for example: the series of statutory instruments made in 2022 follows the series of statutory instruments made in 2021.
